Lauching Windows Server 2016 on Azure


Lab 1 of n 

web page maker

Create a Resource Group

1. Log-on to portal.azure.com

2. Click on "Resource groups"



3. Then click "+Add"



4.  Name your resource group "ad-lab". For region, choose the one nearest you, or you can use an online speed test to choose the location with the lowest latency.  Note: Regions are listed alphabetically and not by geography, so you may to look at the whole list to find the right region.


5. Press the "Review + Create" button at the bottom of the screen.

6. On the next screen review your selections and press the "Create" button at the bottom.

7. You should now see the resource group "ad-lab" listed. If not, it may take Azure a few seconds to provision the resource group. Hitting the "refresh" button should show the new group. 


Ceating the Virtual Machine 

8. On the left panel, click on "Virtual Machines"  and then click "+Add."



9. Select the options shown below. Set your region and choose your own admin username that is unique. Make a note of the admin username. 


10. Click the "Review + create" button.

11. Review the selections and cost. After your free trial is over, this is how much it will cost per hour to run your machine. Keep in mind that as long as the machine is running, you are being billed for the cost -- whether you are using it or not. We will go over how to avoid cost overruns in the next lesson. 

Click "Create."

12.  You'll see your server and other required resources are being deployed. This will take a few minutes. While waiting for it deploy, move on to the next steps. 



Setting up the IP configuration 

To properly deploy Active Directory Domain Services, it will require a static IP private address. Normally this is configured in the Server Manager application on Sever 2016. When Server 2016 is running on an Azure VM, it will need to be set up in Azure.

13. Click on the link for the server's network inface. 

14.  Then click on "IP configurations."

15. The private IP address should be shown as dynamic. Click on it. 

16. Switch the slider to "static" and click "save." 


You are finished with this lab. If you are finished, follow the steps below to shut down the VM. 

Shut down procedure:  1. Click on "Virtual Machines" on the left side panel.  2. Check the box for your VM. 3. Click "stop."
